##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Introduction "RunLameInfiltrator introduction"

                            @{U}The aim of the game@{UU}

Do  you  run  your  system  using  another  screenmode than PAL or NTSC, for
example  EURO72 or an AGA specific screenmode?  Have you ever tried to start
a  game or demo from within this screenmode?  Have you ever been angry about
those  programmers  who  do  not stick to the guidelines of programming thus
producing  programs  which are not aware of the screenmode they were started
out of?

Do  you  have an Amiga with 68010, 68020, 68030 or 68040 processor?  Did you
ever curse those socalled coders whose programs crash your computer when you
didn't  disable  the  processor's  caches and forgot to move the vector base
register back to $0.l?

@{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} programming is the disease, RunLameInfiltrator is the cure!

@{B}NEVER@{UB}  start  RunLameInfiltrator  as stand-alone-program, it definitely @{B}WILL@{UB}
crash  your system.  RunLameInfiltrator @{B}MUST@{UB} be linked to another program to
work correctly.  This process is called `infiltration' in the following, and
the  resulting  file  of  linking  RunLameInfiltrator to a program is called
`infiltrated program'.

RunLameInfiltrator  is  a  Kick1.3+ tool, it may work under Kick1.0/1.1/1.2,
but  I  cannot  give  any  warranty  for  this.   RunLameInfiltrator is 100%
pc-relative  and  reentrant  Assembler  code,  so  you  can  link it to pure
programs  and they will stay pure after linking.

Just after having degraded the display and the CPU RunLameInfiltrator starts
the  program  it has been linked to.  When the program it has been linked to
has  been  finished  the  display  and  CPU state is restored to the same as
before starting the infiltrated program.

Summarizing  we  can  say  RunLameInfiltrator  is  a  multitasking  friendly
temporary  system  degrader which, linked permanently to files, may let some
bad  behaving  programs run in your system's environment (but can't give any
guarantee).   If   some   of   those   @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation}   programs   don't  run  though
RunLameInfiltrator has been used, they are on a higher lameness-level, which
can't  be  fixed  by  RunLameInfiltrator  (this  is  definitely @{B}NOT@{UB} a bug of
RunLameInfiltrator).

I do write demos myself and you can believe, @{B}i do know@{UB} how to write a proper
startup code.  Consider RunLameInfiltrator beeing a startup code.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Features "RunLameInfiltrator features"

                                  @{U}Features@{UU}

The @{B}{}@{UB}'s inform you about the system configuration needed for a feature.

 ∑Disabling of all processor caches, burst or copyback modes.
  {68020, 68030[EC], 68040[EC]}

 ∑Moving @{"VBR" LINK VBR_Explanation} to location $0.
  {68010, 68020, 68030[EC], 68040[EC]}

 ∑Degrading display's screenmode to simulate @{"OCS" LINK OCS_Explanation}.
  {@{"ECS" LINK ECS_Explanation}, @{"AGA" LINK AGA_Explanation}}

 ∑Degrading sprite resolution to simulate @{"OCS" LINK OCS_Explanation}.
  {@{"AGA" LINK AGA_Explanation}}

 ∑Turning off sprites in a system friendly manner.
  {@{"OCS" LINK OCS_Explanation}, @{"ECS" LINK ECS_Explanation}, @{"AGA" LINK AGA_Explanation}}

 ∑Permanent fix for @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} programs. Fix can be removed.

 ∑Infiltration of pure programs preserves the reentry ability.

 ∑Infiltration of pc-relative programs preserves the location relativity.

 ∑Works under Kickstarts 1.3, 1.4, 2.04, 3.0 and 3.1.

 ∑Due  to  100% system conform and system friendly algorithms, future system
  compatibility  is  as  high  as  possible.   Furthermore  the multitasking
  environment  is not hurt or damaged by the code.  All degrading is done as
  smart as possible, and the code did never crash during @{"beta testing" LINK BetaTesting}.

 ∑verified,  tested  and  safe  (100%  assembler)  code  resulted in a short
  binary (so the infiltrated programs only become a little longer).

Sounds great?  YAH - Yet another hype?  @{B}Hypenosis@{UB} - @{I}Better believe the hype!@{UI}
But keep on reading, here come... @{"the bad news" LINK Disadvantages}.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Disadvantages "RunLameInfiltrator disadvantages"

                                @{U}The bad news@{UU}

 ∑Because  Workbench  programs  do  inderectly  ignite  an  UnLoadSeg() onto
  themselves, the code could be flushed by this (f.i.  Mungwall).  Therefore
  restoring  the  system  is not yet possible when run from Workbench.  This
  includes  a  @{B}WANTED@{UB}  mem  leak  in the infiltrated program.  You will lose
  around 7K bytes of memory.

 ∑The   infiltrated   programs'   code   is  changed  permanently  (but  not
  irreversibly). If you don't like this, use RunLame.

 ∑No GUI for FileLinker and FileUnlinker (the infiltration support tools).

 ∑Dangerous FileUnlinker tool (if you don't know what you are doing).

 ∑The  updating  of  infiltrated programs is slightly uncomfortable (unlink,
  and link again).

 ∑Though  the  code  worked  very well during the @{"beta testing" LINK BetaTesting} phase, there
  might be nasty bugs.

 ∑RunLameInfiltrator  can't be used to fix non-DOS trackloading demos, for I
  don't  want  to  support this kind of loaders.  I usally like to keep good
  demos  on my harddisk, which is not directly possible with @{I}trackmos@{UI}.  So I
  don't keep lame coded @{I}trackmos@{UI}.

 ∑The documentation often might use improper terms.  Please excuse this, for
  I  am  not  a  native  english  speaker.   If  you  want  to  improve  the
  documentation, please @{"contact" LINK ContactAuthor} me.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Installation "Installing RunLame"

                             @{U}Installing RunLame@{UU}

Installing  RunLameInfiltrator  in  your  system is quite easy.  There is no
need for an Installer script.

At  first  enter the directory, which contains the package.  The name of the
directory  is  @{B}RunLame_V#?.#?@{UB}   (the  #?.#?  is the current release number).
Then  enter the @{B}Bin@{UB} directory and copy to the following files to a directory
which is in your system path:

 ∑RunLameInfiltrator
 ∑FileLinker
 ∑FileUnlinker

That's  it.  You  can  now infiltrate programs.  Refer to the @{"configuration" LINK Configuring}
instructions and the @{"operation description" LINK OperationDescription}.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE OperationDescription "RunLameInfiltrator operation description"

                       @{U}How to use RunLameInfiltrator@{UU}
@{B}
____________________________________________________________________________

ATTENTION!!   NEVER  START  RUNLAMEINFILTRATOR  ALONE  AS PROGRAM!!  IT WILL
CRASH YOUR SYSTEM!!  RUNLAMEINFILTRATOR MUST BE LINKED TO VALID PROGRAMS.
____________________________________________________________________________
@{UB}

In   comparison   to   @{"RunLame" LINK RunLame.guide/Main}  which   is   included   in   this  package,
RunLameInfiltrator  performs  the  following  actions  (which  are RunLame's
@{"default" LINK RunLame.guide/Option_DEFAULTS} options):

 S    = @{" SCREEN          " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_SCREEN} : degrade display
 V    = @{" VISIBLE         " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_VISIBLE} : the current display stays visible
 NC   = @{" NOCACHE         " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_CACHE} : disable instruction & data cache
 NIC  = @{" NOINSTCACHE     " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_INSTCACHE} : disable instruction cache
 NDC  = @{" NODATACACHE     " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_DATACACHE} : disable data cache
 NB   = @{" NOBURST         " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_BURST} : disable instruction & data burst mode
 NIB  = @{" NOINSTBURST     " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_INSTBURST} : disable instruction burst mode
 NDB  = @{" NODATABURST     " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_DATABURST} : disable data burst mode
 NCB  = @{" NOCOPYBACK      " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_COPYBACK} : disable copyback mode
 NEC  = @{" NOEXTERNALCACHE " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_EXTERNALCACHE} : disable external caches
 NVBR = @{" VBRTO0          " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_VBR} : move VBR to $0.L
 CL   = @{" COMMANDLINE cmd " LINK RunLame.guide/Option_COMMANDLINE} : cmd is executed, where cmd is the program

The  above  explained options are active during the execution of @{B}cmd@{UB} and the
changed settings of your system are reset to the state active before.  So if
you  know  that  for example the demo called @{B}ObsoleteFX@{UB} will not run on your
normal system configuration, infiltrate @{B}RunLameInfiltrator@{UB} to @{B}ObsoleteFX@{UB} and
try  if it will work.  To @{"link" LINK FileUnLinkerGeneral} @{B}RunLameInfiltrator@{UB} to @{B}ObsoleteFX@{UB}, you can use
the following procedure:

 @{B}FileLinker RunLameInfiltrator name_of_lame_program name_of_output_program@{UB}

 (name_of_output_program is called @{B}the infiltrated program@{UB})

In this special case use:

 @{B}FileLinker RunLameInfiltrator ObsoleteFX ObsoleteFX.rli@{UB}

Now  try  if  the  infiltrated  program  works  on  your  system.   When the
programmer(s) of the un-infiltrated program were too @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} it will of course
not  work  :-).   Assuming that @{B}ObsoleteFX.rli@{UB} now works on your system, the
following will happen when @{B}ObsoleteFX.rli@{UB} is started:

 assumed system settings before starting @{B}ObsoleteFX.rli@{UB}:
  data cache active        | instruction cache active
  data burst mode active   | instruction burst mode inactive
  external caches inactive | copyback mode active
  VBR in Fast RAM at position p

 system settings during execution of @{B}ObsoleteFX@{UB}:
  data cache inactive      | instruction cache inactive
  data burst mode inactive | instruction burst mode inactive
  external caches inactive | copyback mode inactive
  VBR at $0.l
  screenmode changed to PAL,
  sprite resolution changed to lores and sprites turned off

 system settings after execution of @{B}ObsoleteFX.rli@{UB}:
  data cache active        | instruction cache active
  data burst mode active   | instruction burst mode inactive
  external caches inactive | copyback mode active
  VBR in Fast RAM at position p

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE FileUnLinkerGeneral "File(Un)Linker general notes"

                      @{U}General notes on File(Un)Linker@{UU}

At   this   point   I   give   a   short   introduction   to   the  programs
@{B}FileLinker@{UB}/@{B}FileUnlinker@{UB},   which   I   have   written   a   long  time  ago.
@{B}FileLinker@{UB}/@{B}FileUnlinker@{UB}  is  not  pc-relative,  nor  is it reentrant, so you
can't  make  it resident.  It can't be started from the Workbench because it
doesn't  include  the Workbench startup code.  @{B}FileLinker@{UB}/@{B}FileUnlinker@{UB} works
on  Kick  1.3+, it may work on earlier Kickstart versions, but I cannot give
any  warranty for this.  Both programs may contain bugs and do not represent
my current programming skills (in fact when I read the source lately it gave
me  nightmares).   But  because in all the time I was using both programs no
bugs  have  been  found,  I  just  release both programs unchanged with this
package.   An  easier to use and similar tool I have written when I finished
@{B}FileLinker@{UB}/@{B}FileUnlinker@{UB}.   This  advanced tool is called @{B}FileChainer@{UB} and has
been  released  to the public, so when you want to link normal programs, get
FileChainer  for  this purpose.  In the case of @{B}RunLameInfiltrator@{UB} it is not
possible  to use @{B}FileChainer@{UB}, so we have to use the both older and much more
uglier  programs.   Of  course  you  can use any other known program that is
doing  the  same, but, I don't know of any other released program that could
have been used instead.

				@{" FileLinker   " LINK FileLinkerDescription}

				@{" FileUnlinker " LINK FileUnlinkerDescription}

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE FileLinkerDescription "FileLinker operation description"

                           @{U}How to use FileLinker@{UU}

What  is  FileLinker doing exactly?  FileLinker is able to insert a @{B}ONE HUNK@{UB}
executable file as first hunk into the hunk collection of another executable
file.  The inserted hunk will be started on execution of the resulting file.
This  first  hunk  must  execute the other hunks itself, if this is desired.
You  see,  that  abilites  of  FileLinker are slightly restricted, but it is
exactly what is needed to infiltrate RunLameInfiltrator into a program.

To infiltrate RunLameInfiltrator to a program use:

 @{B}FileLinker RunLameInfiltrator program_name new_program_name@{UB}

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE FileUnlinkerDescription "FileUnlinker operation description"

                          @{U}How to use FileUnlinker@{UU}

FileUnlinker  irreversibly  removes the first hunk of an executable file, so
RunLameInfiltrator  can  be  removed from an infiltrated program.  @{B}ATTENTION@{UB}
FileUnlinker  doesn't  check if the first hunk of the programm that shall be
processed  really  is  RunLameInfiltrator,  so  use  of  FileUnlinker  on an
un-infiltrated   program   results   in   data  loss  and  the  programm  is
irretrievably destroyed.  Be careful with FileUnlinker in your own interest.
You  do  best  if  you check with the @{B}Version@{UB} CLI command of C= if a program
really is infiltrated, before you unlink any hunks of it.

To remove RunLameInfiltrator from an infiltrated program use:

 @{B}FileUnlinker infiltrated_program_name removed_program_name@{UB}


Example:
@{B}
 FileLinker RunLameInfiltrator FooBar FooBar.rli

 FileUnlinker FooBar.rli FooBar2
@{UB}
@{B}FooBar2@{UB} should be exactly the same as @{B}FooBar@{UB} now.

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE Configuring "Configuring RunLame"

                            @{U}Configuring RunLame@{UU}


@{U}Configuring for shell@{UU}:

RunLameInfiltrator  itself  is  not  configurable,  but you can simplify the
infiltration  and  dehunking.   This  can easily be done using some aliases.
Replace @{B}[path]@{UB} with the path to the apropriate file.
@{B}
Alias infiltrate '%file [path]FileLinker [path]RunLameInfiltrator $file'

Alias dehunk     '%file [path]FileUnlinker $file'

Alias update     '%file [path]FileUnlinker $file;
                        [path]FileLinker [path]RunLameInfiltrator $file'
@{UB}


@{U}Configuring for Directory Opus@{UU}:

Enter  the  configuration  module and the @{B}Buttons@{UB} section.  Press one of the
still  unused  buttons.   Enter `@{B}Infiltrate@{UB}' for @{B}Name@{UB} string gadget.  Make a
@{B}New     entry@{UB}     which     is     @{B}AmigaDOS@{UB}.      Enter    `@{B}[path]FileLinker
[path]RunLameInfiltrator  {f}@{UB}' in the @{B}entry@{UB} string gadget (replace @{B}[path]@{UB} by
the  path  were  the appropriate file is located).  Enter @{B}@{U}S@{UU}tack size@{UB} `@{B}4000@{UB}',
@{B}@{U}P@{UU}riority@{UB}  `@{B}0@{UB}',  @{B}@{U}C@{UU}lose  delay@{UB}  `@{B}-1@{UB}'.   Uncheck  all  entries  in the @{B}Flags...@{UB}
listview  gadget.   Check  @{B}Output  window@{UB}  and  @{B}Do all files@{UB} in the listview
gadget.  Click @{B}Okay@{UB}.

Click  on another free button.  Enter `@{B}Unlink@{UB}' for @{B}Name@{UB} string gadget.  Make
a  @{B}New entry@{UB} which is @{B}AmigaDOS@{UB}.  Enter `@{B}[path]FileUnlinker {f}@{UB}' in the @{B}entry@{UB}
string  gadget  (replace  @{B}[path]@{UB}  by  the  path were the appropriate file is
located).  Enter @{B}@{U}S@{UU}tack@{UB} size `@{B}4000@{UB}', @{B}@{U}P@{UU}riority@{B} `@{B}0@{UB}', @{B}@{U}C@{UU}lose delay@{UB} `@{B}-1@{UB}'.  Uncheck
all  entries  in  the @{B}Flags...@{UB}  listview gadget.  Check @{B}Output window@{UB} and @{B}Do
all files@{UB} in the listview gadget.  Click @{B}Okay@{UB}.

Click  on another free button.  Enter `@{B}Update@{UB}' for @{B}Name@{UB} string gadget.  Make
a @{B}New entry@{UB} which is @{B}AmigaDOS@{UB}.  Enter `@{B}[path]FileUnlinker {fu}@{UB}' in the @{B}entry@{UB}
string  gadget  (replace  @{B}[path]@{UB}  by  the  path were the appropriate file is
located).   Make  a  @{B}New  entry@{UB}  which is @{B}AmigaDOS@{UB}.  Enter `@{B}[path]FileLinker
[path]RunLameInfiltrator  {f}@{UB}' in the @{B}entry@{UB} string gadget (replace @{B}[path]@{UB} by
the  path  were  the appropriate file is located).  Enter @{B}@{U}S@{UU}tack size@{UB} `@{B}4000@{UB}',
@{B}@{U}P@{UU}riority@{UB}  `@{B}0@{UB}',  @{B}@{U}C@{UU}lose  delay@{UB}  `@{B}-1@{UB}'.   Uncheck  all  entries  in the @{B}Flags...@{UB}
listview  gadget.   Check  @{B}Output  window@{UB}  and  @{B}Do all files@{UB} in the listview
gadget. Click @{B}Okay@{UB}. Click @{B}Okay@{UB}. Click @{B}Save@{UB}. Click @{B}Okay@{UB}.

Now  you should have 3 new buttons in the button bar.  The @{B}Infiltrate@{UB} button
links RunLameInfiltrator to all selected files.  Make sure the files are not
write  and  delete  protected.  The @{B}Unlink@{UB} button is somewhat @{B}DANGEROUS@{UB}.  It
will  strip  the  first hunk of each selected file.  Make sure the files you
want  to  dehunk  are not write and delete protected.  @{B}THE HUNK STRIPPED OFF
THE FILES IS NOT RECOVERABLE, SO THINK TWICE BEFORE YOU PRESS THIS BUTTON!!@{UB}
The  @{B}Update@{UB}  button  will replace an old version of RunLameInfiltrator in an
infiltrated  file  with the latest installed version.  @{B}BE SURE NOT TO UPDATE
NON-INFILTRATED FILES, THEY WILL BE CORRUPTED!!@{UB}

@ENDNODE
##_____________________________________________________________________________

@NODE ProblemsSolutions "RunLameInfiltrator `Problems - solutions - corner'"

                       @{U}Problems - solutions - corner@{UU}

 ∑If you got this error message:
@{B}
                        Screenmode degrading failed!
                 Forbid all promotion utilities to promote:
             "RunLameInfiltrator (© by Bilbo 1st of Hypenosis)"
               Display of this lame program might be trashed!
@{UB}
  Then you have probably installed one of the screenmode promotion utilities
  (fi.   The Promotor, NewMode, ForceMonitor, PKludge).  This promotion tool
  will  then  promote  the compatibility screen too, what is a really stupid
  idea.  You should prevent the promotion utility from promoting all screens
  with the title "@{B}RunLameInfiltrator (© by Bilbo 1st of Hypenosis)@{UB}".

 ∑The  sprite  DMA  shows weird patterns, though you infiltrated the program
  (which  should  turn  off  the sprites, too).  If this happens, one of the
  currently  open  windows  became  active.  All windows have an own pointer
  image,  which becomes active on window activation.  You may have installed
  an AutoPointer/SunMouse utility which activated a window after the sprites
  have  already  been  turned  off.   Avoid this by disabling the apropriate
  application (the window-activating one).  Another possibility is, that the
  infiltrated program opened a window which became active.  You can't easily
  work around the latter problem.

 ∑The  program  you want to infiltrate is self-detaching and the settings of
  RunLameInfiltrator  are  only valid until the program has detached itself.
  If  the  program has an option to turn off detaching, then use this option
  at  starting  the  program  to prevent detach.  Otherwise, bad luck.  Some
  self-detaching programs even refuse to work after having been infiltrated.
  Other  programs work totally okay after beeing infiltrated.  The behaviour
  depends on the detaching mechanism used by the program.

 ∑You have  @{"Enforcer" LINK Enforcer_Explanation} running and your system always hangs when you start an
  infiltrated program.   See the @{"Knows Bugs" LINK KnownBugs} section for an explanantion for
  this phenomenon.  Quit @{"Enforcer" LINK Enforcer_Explanation} before you start an infiltrated program.

 ∑You  tried everything,  but  you  didn't  manage  to  run  a @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} program
  properly.  RunLameInfiltrator  is  not  able to fix very @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} programming
  bugs, so you can assume, the programmer of the program is @{"lame" LINK Lame_Explanation} himself, or
  didn't  have  enough  time to do a proper code.  But nobody is perfect :-)
  Your  last  chance  might be to try other degraders available in the Amiga
  world.   All degraders known to me are listed below and are available from
  AmiNet (lowest required Kickstart release in @{B}[]@{UB}s):

	Degrader   V1.30  [V1.2 - V3.0, depends on used features]
	RunIt      V1.4   [V1.2]
	RunShit    V1.03  [V1.2]
	KillAGA    V2.0   [V3.0]
	WBKillAGA  V1.0   [V3.0] (needs KillAGA)

  I  doubt  that  you  will  have more luck using those programs, but if so,
  @{"contact" LINK ContactAuthor} me and let me know.

@ENDNODE

